snippet.textDisplay:
I find it quite amusing how Ireland, for Americans at least, has so many things attributed to it that are staples of almost all of Europe. Milk Stout, for instance, was widely consumed throughout Europe as part of a balanced diet around 200 years ago, but now its connotations have shifted solely to Guinness and Murphy's, both from ROI. Potatoes are another funny one. Potatoes were, and to an extent still are, fundamental to the working class diet of all European nations., Eastern European Zakuski, English 'Tatoes, Scottish Tatties, Irish 'Taters. Boulangeres. And yet, whenever Americans think of Ireland, their image is of the Potato, but for other European nations, less so.



Still don't know why those things are. The Potato I can attribute to the famine, but like, that was a pan-European thing, and originally started in the American Mid-West anyway.


Also, fun fact, the "E" in some Whisk(e)ys was a marketting ploy by Irish Whiskey companies to try and distinguish their product on the market from Scotch and other British Whiskys. The different flavour from Irish to Scotch comes from the fact that part of Ireland's whiskey contains unmalted grain, which was added because of English Tax Laws on grain in spirits.
